00:00:06.740 --> 00:00:09.330
&gt;&gt; Okay, J.P.
&gt;&gt; That's better.

00:00:09.330 --> 00:00:09.840
So how are you and

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:13.740
the developer doing besides all
the craziness with launching 0.5?

00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:15.310
&gt;&gt; Pretty good.

00:00:15.310 --> 00:00:18.360
I submitted Shopping List Plus Plus
to the Abbie's like you suggested.

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:21.540
We're a bit of a long shot what with
Grocery Grabber having just released

00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:23.990
their next version, but you never know.

00:00:23.990 --> 00:00:25.460
&gt;&gt; That's awesome.

00:00:25.460 --> 00:00:29.060
&gt;&gt; And let's see, besides that, well we
finished everything on the wire frames.

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:29.900
&gt;&gt; Woo hoo.

00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:31.360
That's great to hear.

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:34.410
Why don't you take me through everything
you guys have done for old times sake?

00:00:34.410 --> 00:00:35.880
&gt;&gt; Sure thing.

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:39.520
Shopping List Plus Plus is turning
into a fully fledged experience, and

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.150
it's all thanks to you, the developer.

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:47.850
Starting with version 0.1, you made a
very basic prototype that just read and

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:48.455
wrote some data.

00:00:48.455 --> 00:00:54.000
In version 0.2, you flush this out
more by incorporating FirebaseUI so

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.798
that you could list out shopping
lists and shopping list items.

00:00:56.798 --> 00:01:02.520
In version 0.3, you added user
accounts as well as a bunch of

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:06.050
functionality like letting others know
that you're in the store shopping and

00:01:06.050 --> 00:01:07.412
marking that you've bought items.

00:01:07.412 --> 00:01:12.610
Version 0.4 might have been
our most triumph moment

00:01:12.610 --> 00:01:15.816
when you overhaul the data structure
to allow for shopping list sharing.

00:01:15.816 --> 00:01:19.377
You also added some pretty
snazzy sorting features.

00:01:19.377 --> 00:01:24.640
In version 0.5,
you added offline functionality so

00:01:24.640 --> 00:01:27.540
that the app caches data even
when it's not on the screen.

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:31.780
Also implemented a bunch of read,
write and

00:01:31.780 --> 00:01:35.490
validation rules to make sure that
our data is properly formed and

00:01:35.490 --> 00:01:37.815
that only the correct
people have access to it.

00:01:37.815 --> 00:01:43.250
&gt;&gt; Nice, so I gotta ask, what about
that big security flaw you talked about?

00:01:43.250 --> 00:01:44.490
&gt;&gt; Well, for the short term,

00:01:44.490 --> 00:01:48.260
I basically got another engineer to
separate our password and email flow.

00:01:48.260 --> 00:01:51.280
But we'll be looking into
incorporating a simplistic server,

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:53.050
maybe the later version.

